<p class="p1"><span class="s1"><b>AtkPantoF<span class="Apple-tab-span">	</span><span class="Apple-tab-span">	</span><span class="Apple-tab-span">	</span></b></span><b>Ambisonic Tool Kit B-format Pantophonic Farfield Decode</b></p>
<p class="p2"><b></b><br></p>
<p class="p3"><br></p>
<p class="p4"><b>AtkPantoF.ar(w, x, y, numChans, orientation, directivity)</b></p>
<p class="p3"><br></p>
<p class="p4">Decode a two dimensional ambisonic B-format signal to a farfield set of speakers in a regular, horizontal polygon. The "farfield" decode is preferred for large scale and concert hall decoding.</p>
<p class="p3"><br></p>
<p class="p4">The outputs will be in counter-clockwise order. [Note: counter-clockwise numbering of loudspeakers is the ambisonic convention, but is different from SC3's included ambisonic decoder, <b>DecodeB2</b>.] The position of the first speaker is either center or left of center.</p>
<p class="p3"><br></p>
<p class="p4"><b>numChans</b> - number of output speakers. Typically 4 to 8.</p>
<p class="p4"><b>w, x, y</b> - the B-format signals. </p>
<p class="p4"><b>orientation</b> - 0 or 1, Should be 1 if the front is a vertex of the polygon. The first speaker will be directly in front. Should be 0 if the front bisects a side of the polygon. Then the first speaker will be the one left of center. Default is 0.</p>
<p class="p4"><b>directivity</b> - The weighting of the ambisonic decoding equations. Varies between -1 for idealized, strict soundfield decoding to +1 for controlled opposites, in-phase decoding. A value of 0 will give optimized energy decoding. Defaults to +1. Controlled opposites is the option preferred for acoustically live spaces.</p>
<p class="p3"><br></p>
<p class="p3"><br></p>
<p class="p5">{<span class="Apple-converted-space"> </span></p>
<p class="p5">#w, x, y, z = <span class="s2">AtkMonoToB</span>.ar(<span class="s2">PinkNoise</span>.ar * <span class="s2">LFSaw</span>.kr(-10).range(0, 0.2), <span class="s2">MouseX</span>.kr(0, 2pi));</p>
<p class="p5"><span class="s2">AtkPanToF</span>.ar(4, w, x, y, 1, -1);</p>
<p class="p5">}.play(s);</p>
